For all NE businesses. Social distancing: reservations only, cloth face coverings required of all employees, no more than 20 customers or 25 pct maximum capacity (whichever is smaller), at least 6 ft betweeen individuals and household groups, establish a COVID-19 mitigation plan. Hygiene: employer must provide handwashing capability or sanitizer, frequent handwashing for employees, employer must provide hourly touch-point sanitation. Staffing: must conduct pre-shift screening, no employee allowed to come to work within 72 hours of having a fever. Cleaning and disinfecting: must be conducted in compliance with CDC protocols, active cleaning immediately or shutting down for 72 hours if employee becomes COVID-19 positive with testing.

General: social distancing protocol maintained, develop COVID-19 mitigan plan for employees and customers. Capacity: groups are limited to household members only, maximum indoor capacity is 25%, no more than 20 tables outside. Operations: reservations only (no walk-ins allowed), cloth coverings required of all employees, disposableware and single use condiments, fully sanitize tables after each group, sanitize or provide disposable menus, hourly touch-point sanitization. Hygiene: must provide handwashing capacity or sanitizer, frequent handwashing required. Staffing: conduct pre-shift screening, no person can work if ill or within 72 hours of having a fever. Cleaning and disinfecting: must follow CDC protocols

Non-essential businesses can resume operations if they meet specified social distancing requirements, hygiene protocols, staffing requirements, cleaning and disinfecting. Retail businesses have same protocols, but also are encouraged to do entryway, curbside and home delivery, telephone and online ordering for contactless pickup and delivery, cashless and receiptless transactions. Personal care services also have specific guidelines (e.g., no people allowed in waiting area, one customer per staff person at a time, customers have to undergo a pre-visit telephone screening for symptoms consistent with COVID-19, customers must also wear cloth coverings).

California moves to Stage 2, easing restrictions on lower risk workplaces with health and safety adapations: retail (curbside and pick-up), manufacturing, offices, select services (carwash, pet grooming, landscape gardening), outdoor museums and open gallery places. Transition to Stage 2 required a state-wide modification to the statewide stay-at-home order, which occurred on 20200507. Permits county discretion on stricter orders. Detailed more here: https://covid19.ca.gov/roadmap/

Programs and courses at post-secondary institutions may resume if in-person classes do not exceed 50 pct occupancy or do not exceed 50 people per room. They are considered essential while (quote) providing in person classroom or laboratory education for less than 10 students per classroom or lab in medical training fields only, or performing essential functions (quote)
LastUpdatedNotes: Changed from Eases to Ends PID CO0215

PolicyCodingNotes: Extends non-mandated stay at home for all populations. (quote) All individuals currently living within the State of Colorado are encouraged to stay at home or in the vast, great outdoors and avoid unnecessary interactions whenever possible in order to reduce the spread of disease. (quote)

Extends non-mandated stay at home for at-risk populations. (quote) People at risk of severe illness from COVID-19 are urged to stay in their residence at all times except as necessary to seek medical care. (quote)

Effective July 1, on-premise consumption is no longer allowed and restricted operations are required for bars, taverns, brew pubs, breweries, wineries, tasting rooms, and other places of public accommodation offering alcholic beverages (can have delivery/take-out, off-premise consumption only). Bars may remain open for on-premise consumption if it is a licensed food establishment, wherein food is served and tables are set with at least 6 ft physical distancing between tables.
Extends state of emergency for additional 30 days from July 6, so extended to 20200805

Extends closure for onsite consumption and restricted operations are required for bars, taverns, brew pubs, breweries, wineries, tasting rooms, and other places of public accommodation offering alcholic beverages (can have delivery/take-out, off-premise consumption only). This category of businesses may remain open for on-premise cconsumption if it is a licensed food establishment, wherein food is served and tables are set with at least 6 ft physical distancing between tables. Note that PHO was issued on 20200710, but is in effect 20200706 per EO-PHO dynamic in Colorado. Note that Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Because county variance status is not easily trackable at from the state level at this time, we are not currently tracking these variances.

Extends detailed business health and safety protocols for reopening, including symptom screening, temperature check stations, closure of common areas, cleaning protocols, mandatory social distancing, provision of PPE. Also extends mask requirements for employees in several sectors (e.g., government offices and facilities, transport, most businesses that have re-opened). Further detail is on pages 6-9 of the PHO. Note that PHO was issued on 20200710, but is in effect 20200706 per EO-PHO dynamic in Colorado. Note that Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Because county variance status is not easily trackable at from the state level at this time, we are not currently tracking these variances.

Note that Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Because county variance status is not easily trackable at from the state level at this time, we are not currently tracking these variances.

Counties certified to meet Protect Our Neighbors attestation can have gathering activities up to 500 people while maintaining social distancing. Note that PHO was issued on 20200710, but is in effect 20200706 per EO-PHO dynamic in Colorado. Note that a list of these counties is not yet immediately available at the state-level, so we are not tracking their variances at the time of entry. (quote) Counties and regions certified for Protect Our Neighbors may allow any business or activity within their jurisdiction to operate at 50pct of their pre-pandemic capacity, not to exceed 500 people in any one setting. (quote)

Extends previous mask order, as it is not contingent on modifications pertaining to the next phase, and the issued EO indicates all other past orders pertaining to COVID-19 are currently in effect except as modified by that order. This extension is such that at Goverment Offices and Facilities, all employees that interact in close proximity to with other employees or the public and all members of the public must wear medical or non-medical face coverings that cover the nose and mouth, as a condition of ingress or movement within such location. Considered a Mandate1 on PublicMaskLevel coding since it applies to the public in limited settings (government offices and facilities). Note that PHO was issued on 20200710, but is in effect 20200706 per EO-PHO dynamic in Colorado. Note that Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Issues statewide mask order, requiring people in Colorado who are 11 years and older to wear a covering over their noses and mouths when entering or moving within any public indoor space, or while using or waiting to use public (buses, light-rail) or non-personal (taxis, car services, ride-shares) transportation services. Exemptions for individuals who cannot wear masks or face coverings due to medical conditions or disabilities, and does not require masks in outdoor spaces (though encourages such use). Includes worship services. In effect at midnight on 20200716, so coded to 20200717. Coded as a Mandate2 under PublicMaskLevel as it covers broadly covers indoor settings and explicitly does not require mask use in outdoor settings.

Note that Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Because county variance status is not easily trackable at from the state level at this time, we are not currently tracking these variances.On 20200723, amended EO extended this policy to 20200822: https://www.colorado.gov/governor/sites/default/files/inline-files/D%202020%20144%20Amending%20Safer%20at%20Home%20in%20the%20Vast%2C%20Great%20Outdoors.pdf
LastUpdatedNotes: Updated DateExpiry to 20200822, updated PolicyCodingNotes, added Colorado0042 as an additional PolicySourceID

PolicyCodingNotes: Extends state of emergency for additional 30 days from August 4, so extended to 20200903

Extends expanded bar restrictions that ceased sale of alcohol after 10 pm daily. Extends closure for onsite consumption and restricted operations are required for bars, taverns, brew pubs, breweries, wineries, tasting rooms, and other places of public accommodation offering alcholic beverages (can have delivery/take-out, off-premise consumption only). This category of businesses may remain open for on-premise cconsumption if it is a licensed food establishment, wherein food is served and tables are set with at least 6 ft physical distancing between tables. Note that Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Because county variance status is not easily trackable at from the state level at this time, we are not currently tracking these variances.

Extends detailed business health and safety protocols for reopening, including symptom screening, temperature check stations, closure of common areas, cleaning protocols, mandatory social distancing, provision of PPE. Also extends mask requirements for employees in several sectors (e.g., government offices and facilities, transport, most businesses that have re-opened). Note that Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Because county variance status is not easily trackable at from the state level at this time, we are not currently tracking these variances.

Extends case-based isolation, as it is not contingent on modifications pertaining to the next phase, and the issued EO indicatos all other past orders pertaining to COVID-19 are currently in effect except as modified by that order. Note that Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Because county variance status is not easily trackable at from the state level at this time, we are not currently tracking these variances.

Extends gathering restriction for no more than 10 people at the state-level, though allows counties that meet Protect Our Neighbors attestation to have up to 500 people gatherings with social distancing.. Note Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Because county variance status is not easily trackable at from the state level at this time, we are not currently tracking these variances.

Extends permission for counties certified to meet Protect Our Neighbors attestation to have gathering activities up to 500 people while maintaining social distancing.  Note that a list of these counties is not yet immediately available at the state-level, so we are not tracking their variances at the time of entry

Extends eased private campground operations. For counties that complete Protect Our Neighbors attestation, capacity limits are even higher, at 50 pct of pre-pandemic capacity, with at least 6 ft distancing, and no more than 500 people in one setting for activities. Note that Colorado moves to Protect Our Neighbors phase, which involves both state-level mandates and devolution to county variance. Because county variance status is not easily trackable at from the state level at this time, we are not currently tracking these variances.

Extends statewide mask order, requiring people in Colorado who are 11 years and older to wear a covering over their noses and mouths when entering or moving within any public indoor space, or while using or waiting to use public (buses, light-rail) or non-personal (taxis, car services, ride-shares) transportation services. Exemptions for individuals who cannot wear masks or face coverings due to medical conditions or disabilities, and does not require masks in outdoor spaces (though encourages such use). Includes worship services. Coded as a Mandate2 under PublicMaskLevel as it covers broadly covers indoor settings and explicitly does not require mask use in outdoor settings.

Eases bar restrictions for counties in Protect Our Neighbors phase, allowing them to re-open at 50 pct capacity. As of 20200915, this applies to 5 counties: Gilpin, Gunnison, Mesa, Moffat, Rio Blanco. These designations are based on the new COVID19 Dial, which is regularly updated but counties cannot fully move to a new phase until they have been in the same one for at least 2 weeks. https://covid19.colorado.gov/data/covid-19-dial/covid-19-dial-dashboard

Continues bar restrictions for the remaining 59 counties, requiring bars without food licenses to remain closed for in-person services. This category of businesses may remain open for on-premise cconsumption if it is a licensed food establishment, wherein food is served and tables are set with at least 6 ft physical distancing between tables, but the sale of alcohol must end at 11 pm daily.

Extends detailed business health and safety protocols for reopening, including symptom screening, temperature check stations, closure of common areas, cleaning protocols, mandatory social distancing, provision of PPE. Now exact requirements vary in accordance with the COVID19 dial https://covid19.colorado.gov/data/covid-19-dial/covid-19-dial-dashboard

Counties in Protect Our Neighbors phase continue to have gathering limits of 500, and up to 500 people for indoor religious gatherings. Outdoor religious gatherings do not have numeric capacity limits, but 6 ft distancing must occur. As of 20200915, this applies to 5 counties: Gilpin, Gunnison, Mesa, Moffat, Rio Blanco. These designations are based on the new COVID19 Dial, which is regularly updated but counties cannot fully move to a new phase until they have been in the same one for at least 2 weeks. https://covid19.colorado.gov/data/covid-19-dial/covid-19-dial-dashboard

Counties in Safer at Home Level 2 are permitted to have up to 10 people personal gatherings, and up to 50 people indoors (or 50 pct capacity, whichever is lower) for religious gatherings. Outdoor religious gatherings have no numeric limit but must have 6 ft social distancing. As of 20200915, this applies to 34 counties: Adams, Alamosa, Archuleta, Boulder, Broomfield, Chaffee, Conejos, Costilla, Custer, Denver, Eagle, Garfield, Grand, Jackson, Jefferson, Lake, La Plata, Logan, Montezuma, Montrose, Morgan, Phillips, Pitkin, Prowers, Pueblo, Rio Grande, Routt, Saguache, San Juan, San Miguel, Sedgwick, Summit, Washington, Weld

Counties in Safer at Home Level 1 are permitted to have up to 25 people personal gatherings, and up to 175 people indoors (or 50 pct capacity, whichever is lower) for religious gatherings. Outdoor religious gatherings have no numeric limit but must have 6 ft social distancing. As of 20200915, this applies to 25 counties: Arapahoe, Baca, Bent, Cheyenne, Clear Creek, Crowley, Delta, Dolores, Douglas, Elbert, El Paso, Fremont, Hinsdale, Huerfano, Kiowa, Kit Carson, Larimer, Las Animas, Lincoln, Mineral, Otero, Ouray, Park, Teller, Yuma
Extends eased private campground operations
Extends eased restrictions on indoor and outdoor events such as receptions, events, non-critical auctions, theaters, trade shows, markets, indoor malls, rodeos, fairs, festivals and parades.
Extends easing of camp businesses, residential camps can continue to open.
Eases restrictions of retail for in-person services up to 50 pct capacity. All county groups -- Safer at Home Levels 2 and 1, and Protect Our Neighbors -- are have the same capacity restrictions.

Extends eased restrictions commercial businesses to allow up to 50 percent of employees to conduct in-person work in accordance with mandatory social distancing requirements and protocols. All counties have a 50 pct capacity limit, irrespective of COVID19 dial designation

Eases restrictions on personal care services, allowing all counties up to 50 pct capacity for in-person services. The total possible number of people allowed varies by county designation - Safer at Home Levels 2 and 1 are no more than 50 people in a room, while Protect Our Neighbors counties can have up to 500 people.

Eases restrictions on manufacturing businesses, allowing capacity up to 50 pct capacity for all counties. The total possible number of people allowed varies by county designation - Safer at Home Level 2 can have up to 50 people per room, Safer at Home Level 1 can have up to 175, and Protect our Neighbors can have up to 500.
Extends eased restrictions on sporting events, allowing professional sports to resume pre-season practices, training, and league play after following a reopening plan.

Counties in Protect Our Neighbors phase can have all businesses open at 50 pct of pre-pandemic capacity, with at least 6 ft distancing, and no more than 500 people in one setting for activities. This means previously closed businesses can re-open in these locations: (quote) Establishments primarily based on smoking, such as cigar bars, hookah bars, and cannabis social use licensees, and casinos, amusement parks, arcades, and the use of bounce houses and ball pits in any public or commercial venue. (quote)  As of 20200915, this applies to 5 counties: Gilpin, Gunnison, Mesa, Moffat, Rio Blanco. These designations are based on the new COVID19 Dial, which is regularly updated but counties cannot fully move to a new phase until they have been in the same one for at least 2 weeks. https://covid19.colorado.gov/data/covid-19-dial/covid-19-dial-dashboard

Extends stay-at-home recommendation for all populations (quote) individuals are encouraged to stay at home as much as possible and practice Social Distancing to reduce the likelihood of disease transmission, but certain activities, such as gathering in groups of no more than ten for activities, are permitted (quote). Extends statewide mask order, requiring people in Colorado who are 11 years and older to wear a covering over their noses and mouths when entering or moving within any public indoor space, or while using or waiting to use public (buses, light-rail) or non-personal (taxis, car services, ride-shares) transportation services. Exemptions for individuals who cannot wear masks or face coverings due to medical conditions or disabilities, and does not require masks in outdoor spaces (though encourages such use). Includes worship services. Coded as a Mandate2 under PublicMaskLevel as it covers broadly covers indoor settings and explicitly does not require mask use in outdoor settings.

The 20200717 version of the Framework for Returning to Classroom Instruction plan. Schools in Maine will be categorized into red, yellow and green. Red means high rate of transmission in community and distance learning adopted. Yellow means elevated risk of spread in community and hybrid learning adopted. Any individual who leaves their home or place of residence must wear a face covering over their nose and mouth when in any indoor public space, when outdoors and unable to consistently maintain a distance of six feet or more from individuals who are not members of their household, and when waiting for or riding on public transportation, while in a taxi or ridesharing vehicle, or when using a private car service as a means of hired transportation. Makes exemptions for children under 5 years old, individuals who cannot medically tolerate a face covering, during exercise, etc. Coded as a Mandate3 for PublicMaskLevel as it explicitly requires masks or face coverings in any indoor or outdoor space when unable to maintain physical distancing in public.

Mandates for re-opening for Phase One for Gyms and fitness studios, Pools at gyms, Theaters, including movie theaters, Museums, as detailed in EO's appendices. Broader mandates include reduced capacity and strict distancing.

Effective May 15, 2020, the following businesses can become operational during Phase I under strict physical distancing and reduced capacity protocols in accordance with the Phase One Directive and the Guidance attached to this Directive: Gyms and fitness studios, Pools at gyms, Theaters, including movie theaters, Museums

Other places of assembly such as performance theaters, concert halls, bowling alleys, bingo halls, music halls, and pools that are not in gyms or at a licensed public accommodation shall remain closed.
Bars, breweries, distilleries, and like venues remain in the same operational status as Phase One, but with an increase to 75 percent capacity.
Provides by-sector re-opening directives and guidelines for re-opening and easing restrictions on capacity, etc.

LastUpdatedNotes: Removed PID under Eases, added PID to Ends

Casinos remain at the same operational status as Phase One, but now can be at 75 pct capacity

Restaurants and like venues remain in the same operational status as Phase One, but with an increase to 75 percent capacity.

Expands the Health and safety guidances for Montana schools. Affirms that school districts have the authority to make reopening decisions. Details four scenarios school districts may choose between: fully remote, traditional and offsite, traditional and offsite with increased onsite education, and fully onsite. There is a separate later mandate for masks in schools: https://covid19.mt.gov/Portals/223/Documents/2020-8-12%20-%20Masks%20in%20Schools%20FINAL.pdf?ver=2020-08-12-152544-863

Expands previous business health and safety requirements (i.e., by-sector re-opening directives and guidelines for re-opening and easing restrictions on capacity, etc), requiring employees, volunteers, and contractors in public-facing work to wear a face covering (and requiring businesses to provide them for employees).

(quote) all businesses, government offices, or other persons responsible for indoor spaces open to the public shall require and take reasonable measures to ensure that all employees, contractors, volunteers, customers, or other members of the public wear a face covering that covers their mouth and nose at all times while entering or remaining in any indoor spaces open to the public (quote). For all outdoor gatherings of 50 or more people, individuals are required to wear face coverings when it is not possible to maintain at least 6 ft of physical distance. Exemptions for children under 5, for individuals for whom wearing a mask is not medically possible, during exercise, etc. Technically only applies to counties with 4 or more confirmed active cases of COVID-19 (strongly encourages counties with 3 or fewer confirmed active cases to wear masks), but these locations are not clearly listed - subsequently, treating this as a statewide mandate. Coding as a Mandate2 for PublicMaskLevel as its requirements for outdoor settings are very limited.

Further eases gathering restrictions for sporting activities. No-contact practices, contact practices, and competitions for sports defined as Low Risk, Medium Risk, and High Risk by DOHs Guidance for Sports Activities are permitted in both outdoor and indoor settings.  Such activities must comply with all applicable laws, regulations, and Executive Orders. No-contact practices, contact practices, and competitions that are conducted indoors are subject to the current indoor gathering limit of 25pct of the capacity of the room, with such limit not to exceed 25 persons or be smaller than 10 persons. However, if the number of individuals who are necessary for a no-contact practice, contact practice, or competition is greater than 25 persons, such a no-contact practice, contact practice, or competition may proceed, as long as no individuals are present who are not necessary for the no-contact practice, practice, or competition, such as spectators.

PolicyCodingNotes: Requires employees, contractors, volunteers, customers, and visitors to wear a mask, face shield, or face covering in businesses listed in the order (eg grocery stores, fitness organizations, personal service providers, retail, restaurants and bars and like venues, etc), as well as for ride-sharing and public transit, when they are not eating or drinking. Also does not require employees to wear them if they are not interacting with patrons and can maintain at least 6 ft of distancing. Applies to the following counties: Clackamas, Hood River, Lincoln, Marion, Multnomah, Polk, and Washington (mixture of Phase One and Phase Two counties).

Requires the public to wear masks, face shield, or face covering when at a place of business (sectors listed in the order), as well as ride sharing and public transit. Requirement for individuals for 12 and over (recommended for those younger) who are medically able to so. Applies to the following counties: Clackamas, Hood River, Lincoln, Marion, Multnomah, Polk, and Washington (mixture of Phase One and Phase Two counties). Coded to Mandate2 as it applies to indoor public settings as well as shared transportation.

Phase II reopening guidelines

PolicyCodingNotes: Extends eased restrictions on non-critical retail businesses, permitting them to open for in-store pickup and limited browsing. Only allow 1 per customer per 300 sq ft of store area. Expressly requires employees to wear masks per PID RI0016

Eases restrictions on certain personal care businesses (hair salons and barbershops, nail salons, tattoo parlors, tanning parlors, estheticians, and massage therapists ) and gyms and fitness centers allowing them to reopen subject to guidelines. Recreational businesses and historical/cultural establishments may conduct limited outdoor operations and, under certain circumstances. Examples of these operations include outdoor mini golf courses, batting cages, go-kart tracks, rail biking, bumper cars, zoos, horseback riding, and historical sites.
Continues closure for the following businesses: recreation and entertainment establishments (eg, theaters, cinemas, sporting events, bowling alleys, concert venues, museums)

Extends order mandating people to wear masks in public places: (quote) any person who is in a place open to the public, whether indoors or outdoors, shall cover their mouth and nose with a mask or cloth face covering (quote). Also explicitly requires masks or cloth face coverings when inside grocery stores, pharmacies, other retail stores, and on public transit, taxi, ride sharing or similar service. Coded as Mandate3 for PublicMaskLevel as it explicitly calls for mask use across indoor and outdoor settings.
Extends provision that encourages summer camps to reopen subject to rules.

PolicyCodingNotes: Allows bars to operate at 66 percent of capacity.
Reopening guidelines for Phase III that include PPE use, temperature checks, and social distancing requirements.

Eases restrictions on gatherings, allowing gatherings of up to 25 indoors. Also allowing gatherings of up to 50 outdoors, which can expand to 100 for outdoor restaurants if those guidelines are adhered to.

PolicyCodingNotes: Allows the reopening of convention hall, theaters and performance venues provided that they maintain 66 percent capacity or fewer than 125 people.  Fairs and festivals are also able to reopen provided they remain at 66 percent capacity or under 250 people.
Eases restrictions on retail, allowing businesses to open if they allow 1 customer per 100 feet.

Further eases restrictions on personal care businesses, gyms, and fitness centers, allowing them to re-open if they follow safety guidelines and have 1 person per 100 square feet. Also further eases restrictions on recreational businesses and historical/cultural establishments, allowing them to conduct both indoor and outdoor operations up to 66 pct capacity. Examples of these operations include outdoor mini golf courses, batting cages, go-kart tracks, rail biking, bumper cars, zoos, horseback riding, and historical sites.
Extends provision that encourages summer camps to reopen subject to rules.
Night clubs remain closed

Extends order mandating people to wear masks in public places: (quote) any person who is in a place open to the public, whether indoors or outdoors, shall cover their mouth and nose with a mask or cloth face covering (quote). Also explicitly requires masks or cloth face coverings when inside grocery stores, pharmacies, other retail stores, and on public transit, taxi, ride sharing or similar service. Coded as Mandate3 for PublicMaskLevel as it explicitly calls for mask use across indoor and outdoor settings.
Extends provision (from EO 20-35) that encourages summer camps to reopen subject to rules. No more than 14 campers in groups, etc.

Provides for off premises consumption of alcohol, lists rules for takeout drinks. (quote) Any restaurant, bar or establishment that offers beer, mixed beverages or wine pursuant to this Order must do so in accordance with the physical distancing protocols and regulations set forth by RIDOH. (quote) Extends earlier eased rules on bars (quote) Bars may remain open for seated service only and subject to the requirements described in the Phase III Guidelines for Restaurants and the regulations set forth by RIDOH. Given the need to reduce risk to customers, employees and the community once bars and bar areas within restaurants resume operations, the Phase III guidelines in effect for these businesses are required to follow the requirements in the Phase III guidelines. (quote) Any bar not in compliance will be immediately closed.

Extends health and safety rules for businesses as they reopen. For Phase III, businesses must create a COVID control plan. (quote) businesses with employees returning to work must develop a COVID-19 Control Plan which shall be available for inspection by the Task Force created by Executive Order 20-32. (quote)
Extends EO on case isolation

Expands gathering rules. (quote) All indoor and outdoor social gatherings of more than fifteen (15) people in any public or private space are prohibited. Splits gathering easing for religious gathering into a second entry (RI0103)

Eases gathering mandate  (quote) Includes exceptions for receptions for weddings (50 indoor and 100 outdoor under strict distancing guidelines). Indoor gatherings at religious institutions can have 125 max. (quote) religious and faithbased organizations may conduct indoor in-person activities up to 66 pct percent of worship space capacity, subject to a cap of one hundred and twenty-five (125) people and to the Phase III guidelines for religious and faith-based organizations (quote). Outdoor religious events can have 250, but distancing and masking must be in effect. All houses of worship must develop a COVID control plan.

Extends eased rules on convention halls and office-based businesses etc. (quote) Subject to strict adherence to social distancing, masking, screening and sanitation protocols, indoor venues of assembly, including convention centers, concert halls, performance venues, and theaters may operate at up to 66pct of capacity or 1 person per 100 square feet, subject to Phase III guidelines, to a cap of one hundred and twenty-five (125) people. Outdoor venues can have up to 250 people. Continues Phase III easing of office-based businesses. (quote) For office-based businesses, up to 66pct of workers may work on site at the same time as long as physical distancing standards, regulations and other guidance required in Phase III guidelines can be maintained (quote) All must develop a COVID Control Plan.

Continues Phase III easing of retail. (quote) All retail businesses with a physical location in Rhode Island may continue to conduct in-store pickup and limited browsing. All retail businesses may now allow up to one customer per 100 square feet of store area open to customers generally. (quote) Must also develop a COVID Control Plan

Extends eased rules for entertainment businesses, gyms, and personal care services. (quote Subject to strict adherence to social distancing, masking, screening and sanitation protocols, recreational or entertainment businesses and historical/cultural establishments, that are not venues of assembly, may conduct indoor and outdoor operations subject to a capacity limit of up to 66pct or 1 person per 100 square feet, according to Phase III guidelines. (quote) Must also create COVID Control plan. For gyms, Phase III rules continue. (quote) Outdoor group fitness activities are preferred but are limited to one person per 100 square feet, with all physical distancing guidelines to be observed. (quote) Also must create COVID Control plan. Personal care services can have 1 customer per 100 sq ft. (quote) Personal services businesses and operations, including, but not limited to, hair salons and barbershops, nail salons, tattoo parlors, tanning parlors, estheticians, and massage therapists may open subject to all of the requirements of their professional or facility licensing, the requirements of the Phase III guidelines for personal services at https://ReopeningRI.com and regulations set forth by RIDOH. Such personal service businesses may allow up to one customer per 100 square feet. (quote)
Nightclubs must remain closed (see Number 23)
Extends provision (from EO 20-35) that encourages summer camps to reopen subject to rules. No more than 14 campers in groups, etc. Childcare services may also continue to operate on limited capacity.

Extends quarantine requirement. (quote) Any person coming to Rhode Island for a non-work-related purpose from locations with a high community spread rate as set forth on a list maintained by RIDOH at health.ri.gov/covid must immediately self-quarantine for 14 days or until such time as they receive a negative COVID-19 test (quote).

Extends eased rules for indoor and outdoor dining at restaurants. (quote) An establishment's indoor dining capacity is limited to 66pct of an establishment's regular seating capacity. Outdoor dining is still encouraged as long as the restaurant does not service more than its normal operating capacity. (quote) Service to standing customers (e.g., in a bar area) is prohibited with the exceptionof food pick-up, must follow existing Phase III rules and make a COVID Control plan.

Extension of advisory stay at home, only for vulnerable populations. (quote) All vulnerable populations identified by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), which include those who are 65 years of age and older, are still strongly advised to stay at home unless they must go to work, travel for medical treatment or obtain other necessities such as groceries, gas or medication. (quote) In effect through August 28, so coded 20200829.
Continues state of disaster emergency until Sept. 2.

Extension of mandatory mask rule. (quote) Any person who is in a place open to the public, whether indoors or outdoors, shall continue to cover their mouth and nose with a mask or cloth face covering unless doing so would damage the person's health. No person under two years of age or any person whose health would be damaged thereby shall be required to wear a face covering. (quote) In effect until Sept 2.

Expands restrictions on bars (quote) From 11.00 p.m. until closing, a licensee must close their bar area, including but not limited to the bar counter and seating at the bar counter, and ensure that the bar area is not accessible to patrons. At or before 11.00 p.m. every night, all such bars, restaurants and other establishments must rope off the bar area and make seating at the bar counter unavailable to customers. (quote) Any restaurant, bar or establishment that offers beer, mixed beverages or wine pursuant to this Order must do so in accordance with the physical distancing protocols and regulations set forth by RIDOH. (quote) Extends earlier eased rules on bars (quote) Bars may remain open for seated service only and subject to the requirements described in the Phase III Guidelines for Restaurants and the regulations set forth by RIDOH. Given the need to reduce risk to customers, employees and the community once bars and bar areas within restaurants resume operations, the Phase III guidelines in effect for these businesses are required to follow the requirements in the Phase III guidelines. (quote) Any bar not in compliance will be immediately closed.

Texas Ed. Authority releases School Reopening Guidance Summary, which formally confirms the power of local districts to determine the type of instruction for 2020-21 year. (quote) School boards control the school calendar and have the flexibility to delay their school start date. ... School systems may utilize three models to provide instruction for the 2020-2021 school year (on-campus, synchronous, asynchronous) ... School systems must provide on-campus instruction for every student whose parent(s) want them to receive on-campus instruction (quote). At a press conference two weeks later, governor confirms that (quote) The TEA guidance applies long-standing state law and Executive Orders to conclude that the authority to make decisions about when and how schools safely open rests with the constitutionally and statutorily established local school boards. The authority to decide when the school year will begin lies with local school boards. They can choose dates in August, September, or even later. (quote)
Guidelines from TEA include both requirements and recommendations for school districts as they reopen. Expands previous rules.

Bars may offer on-premises services up to 50 pct capacity if the bar or similar establishment is not in an area with high hospitalizations (for the last seven days, 15 pct or more of the hospitalizations have been from COVID?19 in a Trauma Service Area) or the bar is in an area with high hospitalizations, but is located in a county that has filed with DSHS. It is not clear how frequently these county designations will be updated and thus how easily this will be tracked, and thus we are coding this as statewide.

Note that areas desigated as high hospitalization areas (i.e., areas in a Trauma Service Area with the number of COVID-19 patients who are hospitalized with accounting for more than 15 pct of hospital capacity) have a limit of 50 pct versus 75 pct occupancy. Since it is not clear how frequently these lists will be updated, this is being coded as a statewide easing.

Local school divisions will have discretion on how to operationalize within each phase and may choose to offer more limited in-person options than the phase permits, if local public health conditions necessitate. Coded as Mandate2 as it applies widely across indoor spaces.

In July 6 letter to districts, state superintendent and health commissioner provide updates to school reopening guidance, and indicate that all reopening decisions are now to be made at the local and district level. (quote) This process leaves the final decisions about reopening squarely in the hands of local school boards. Local public health conditions, community concerns, and practical facility constraints have to be taken into account in these school reopening decisions, and we believe our local leaders are best positioned to do that thoughtfully (quote) Thus ending the state level control of school closures. Dependent on updated health safety guidelines - also included in the letter.

New guidance released July 6 extends and expands existing rules for schools as they reopen, outlines Phase I, II, and III rules. Includes rule that students and staff must wear face coverings (see page 10).

Slightly expands the public mask mandate, now requiring all people in Washington to wear face coverings when they are outside of their homes in public and non-public settings, explicitly requiring coverings in congregrate living setting (e.g., apartments) in hallways, elevators, etc and broadly outdoors unless exercising, outdoors with at least 6 ft distancing betwen non-household members. Exemptions for children under 5, persons with conditions that prevents wearing a aface covering (e.g., medical, disability, mental health). Coded as a Mandate3 for PublicMaskLevel as it applies broadly across indoor and outdoor settings.

Extends public mask mandate. Every individual aged 5 years and older shall wear a face covering if the individual is indoors or in an enclosed space, other than a private residence. Exemptions for individuals with conditions that would prohibit safe mask use, during speech (including religious) when at least 6 ft distancing can occur. Indoor public gatherings are limited to no more than 25 pct of the total occupancy for the room or building, and for indoor spaces without an occupancy limit for the room or building, public gatherings are limited to no more than 10 people. Exemptions are child care settings, schools, healthcare settings, churches and places of worship, political rallies, etc.
